Author::::TerryMcBurney
DateTime::::2016-01-25T18:18:45Z
I don’t think the debate about Britain’s membership of the EU is really about the balance of costs and benefits since most people would be unable to objectively calculate where their personal balance sits at the individual level. Various groups make arguments at the national level on the basis of their own vested interests which don’t necessarily include the rest of us. At one level there is a psychological fear of being dominated by Europe or by federalist ambitions in Brussels. However Britain has defended itself quite successfully in this respect by ensuring we kept out of both the Euro area (Gordon Brown) and also the Schengen area (Conservatives) and I can’t envisage any other major challenges to our sovereignty that we couldn’t deal with similarly. Free trade threatens uncompetitive corporations but the rest of us benefit from lower prices and more jobs through increased economic growth. For many people I suspect the debate is mainly driven by the fear of immigration to Britain with the right of free movement of EU citizens and also refugees and economic migrants currently coming from outside. It’s concerning that xenophobic and even racist considerations might be the dominant driver, where the only acceptable solutions are border controls and isolation. It needs to be a bigger debate with Britain taking a leading role in finding long-term solutions at the EU level rather than trying to isolate itself.



